Abstract: The Zambian government&apos; 51% nationalization of the country&apos;s copper mines in 1969 was motivated partly for economic purposes&mdash;a kind of learning-by-doing was anticipated&mdash;and partly for political reasons. It appears that the Zambians did obtain a semblance of managerial control and &ldquo;national ownership,&rdquo; but at a very high financial price. The article estimates that the direct revenue loss was over $1 billion through 1981, not counting various disguised costs. The findings are based primarily on an in-depth analysis of the mining companies&apos; annual reports from 1964 through 1981.&copy; 1985 JIBS. Journal of International Business Studies (1985) 16, 137&ndash;163
